The Normative Influence of Epistemic Value Part 2: 
How Epistemic Relativism and Objectivism are Conjoined in Contemporary Philosophy.
Alexander E. Bauer
Lawrence University
See Part 1…
Hales accepts the idea that knowledge-claims can be evaluated only in reference to another set of background principles and argues for relativism in language based off of this idea, however, he rejects the idea that given a two sets of background principles. He maintains that there is no neutral way of choosing between the two or more alternative sets in evaluating p with respect to rational justification. Hales proposes that language is relative, yet there are some concepts that are normative. There are epistemic concepts that humans can generally agree on. Hales suggests that there is a single source of concepts that are true for different epistemic frameworks, even if they don’t reach the same conclusions. Under this conception of relativism, there is no skepticism about the source of truth values even when taking into account epistemic incommensurability. By accepting relativism and rejecting the epistemic incommensurability thesis, Hales avoids slipping into an analogue of Protagorean relativism. His conception of relative truth allows for some truths to be more correct than others. Hales conclusion, while a relative thesis, accounts for all 3 points of the naive view introduced at the beginning of this paper. While truth is relative, relative truths are true in relation to objective facts. 
In the article Defusing Epistemic relativism, Prichard claims that his dialectical epistemic relativism is not as radical as genuine relativism. He writes in response to arguments like Siegel’s:
“if the point of the (relative) principle is explicitly to evade the truth, then it clearly isn’t an epistemic principle since a minimal requirement of an epistemic principle is surely that it purports to assist one in achieving one’s epistemic goals, like gaining true beliefs” (Prichard, 2009, p. 408)
In proposing one’s method of belief-formation as an epistemically legitimate method is thereby to say that it is a necessarily reliable belief-forming method. To maintain that one has formed one’s belief in a reliable fashion implies that the standards for forming those beliefs are objectively reliable. In the case of incommensurate conceptual schemes, it is inevitably going to be the case that one’s opponent will not accept any reliability claims. For Prichard truth is relative, but the epistemic value of a claim can be evaluated though effective debate. Debate is not meaningful if one cannot regard other belief-forming processes as reliable. Prichard claims that debate can result in normative truths, which allow people to evaluate the epistemic value of propositions under debate. Prichard argues that dialectical epistemic relativism avoids this problem and can account for epistemic value. Intuitions about which methods of belief formation are valid may be incommensurate, but Prichard thinks these types of beliefs are open to counterevidence regardless of whether they are well-grounded fundamental principles of belief formation. He writes that:
“once we recognize that even the holders of well-grounded beliefs by epistemic relativist lights need to be open to counterevidence, including counterevidence offered by those who inhabit different epistemic frameworks, then it becomes clear even the epistemic relativist must allow that there is no epistemic justiﬁcation for a ‘closed’ epistemic framework, one that will not countenance engagement with other epistemic frameworks” (Prichard, 2009, p. 411)
Prichard argues that epistemological relativism is incoherent, while dialectal epistemic relativism is not. Relative principles that result from epistemic incommensurability are only epistemic principles if they do not assist in achieving a true belief. For Prichard, language is relative, yet some concepts become normative through effective evaluation. Engagement between works necessitates working with a standard both works can be evaluated under, which implies that one work can be more correct than another. Prichard’s account of relativism accounts for the naive objectivist view discussed at the beginning of this paper. Prichard illustrates that when a belief is conclusively more correct than another, it is more correct because it is based on an objective truth.
In a New Maneuver Against the Epistemic Relativist, the authors Carter and Gordon introduce a very specific type of relativistic thesis. Their conception of truth isn’t just to that certain propositions are true in respect to background principles. Carter and Gordon think that there is a kind of conceptual gain from organizing these propositions in a practical way. People can use information they know more effectively when they understand how it is related. Kvanvig introduces this idea when he observes that “one can know many unrelated pieces of information, but understanding is achieved only when informational items are pieced together by the subject in question.” (Kvanvig, 2003, p. 192) A necessary condition of knowing requires taking the right propositions as true, but knowing also requires that these pieces of information are correlated in a specific way. Carter and Gordon argue that this move from individual concepts to a more general understanding results in a sort of cognitive gain. However, making this move means moving away from the objective source of this information into a more relative conception of the information as a whole. Carter and Gordon write that: “when one understands φ , one has the ability (or disposition) to grasp the explanatory relations that stand between the truly believed propositions” (Carter and Gordon, 2014, p. 6). Carter and Gordon suggest that the informational items people take to be true are objective facts, but the way these propositions are organized is completely relative to a person’s perspective. People can observe objective facts about the world, but only understand them relative to themselves. In this way there is relative truth, but relative truths are still based on objective facts. Carter and Gordon write that:
“A mere recognition that differences in understanding persist is no more interesting as an insight for motivating epistemic relativism than is the insight that not everyone knows all the same things. Accordingly, we can grant all of the key data points that Hacking takes as motivating the denial of objective epistemic reasons, but we need not accept his conclusion; indeed, we have offered a diagnosis of the data that is compatible with a denial of epistemic relativism. After all, any meta-epistemological commitments (objectivist or otherwise) should allow for individuals to differ in what they know.” (Carter and Gordon, 2014, p. 8)
Carter and Gordon argue that the basic information for all beliefs comes from observing objective facts. Empirical evidence, when based on apparent objective facts is the basic information people organize into belief systems. Under this conception of relativism, the main way to tell if something is true is by experience, but there is room for people to agree on what they think is true. Understanding results in relativity, but people sometimes reach the same conclusions. While there are differences in understanding, there are normative conclusions that people come to agree on as normative truths. Normative truths show that regardless of what objective facts our epistemic claims are based off, there are truths that hold between individuals with different perspectives.
3:         All of these theories argue that there are objective truths. However, they also claim that normative truths are the closest thing people can have to objective truth. Normative truth is essential to determining what truths are most likely to be objective and result from evaluating which propositions have a greater epistemic value. If something is normatively true, it is most likely based on an objective fact, even if it does not capture the fact completely. In this way, accounting for epistemic value implies that there are necessary truths. Beliefs with a higher epistemic value are more likely to be considered normative truths, and these normative truths imply that there are objective facts. When people agree that one belief is better than another, they commit themselves to the idea that there is a specific way things are external to minds. Yet there is no way to determine if one’s relative conceptual scheme accurately reflects the way things are external to minds with complete certainty. The closest thing to certainty in a epistemic proposition, is to reach a normative consensus that agrees with the belief. 
A normative consensus can be reached using whatever standards a group agrees on, but must be subject to debate and counterexamples. In a normative environment there are many ways that beliefs are put under scrutiny. If a belief can last a long period of time without successful refutation, one could consider it to be normatively true. If a group as a whole considers a proposition to be true, there is good reason to believe that the proposition correlates with an objective fact, but that doesn’t necessarily mean that the normative proposition is objectively true. While people can know normative propositions, it is not the case that anyone could know objective facts directly. Yet there isn’t a sufficient reason to think that there are no objective truths. There is a way the world is, but sometimes there seems to be an equal amount of empirical evidence for mutually inconsistent beliefs about the external world. Some of these empirically equivalent ideas are normative truths, so how can normative truth imply that there are objective truths? While normative truths might suggest that mutually inconsistent ideas are objectively true, cases of empirical equivalence prevent the processes of determining which concepts have a greater epistemic value. If one is trying to determine which empirically equivalent concept is more correct, no solution can be reached in a reasonable way. This, however, doesn’t mean that we should accept skepticism about truth. Rather, there are a range of concepts that account for empirical observations about the external world in essentially equal ways (although there may be room for determining which is more likely to be right in terms of internal consistency). 
Consider the following chart, where box W contains the set of all possible worlds (each box might represent an infinite set, the boundaries only represent some similarity relations that can be used to distinguish important subsets). P contains the set of all possible worlds that would appear to follow physics as one understands it. P contains physically possible worlds. S1 contains the set of all possible worlds that account for physics and other normative truths. S2 is the set of all possible worlds that account for physics and other normative truths that are empirically equivalent. The point α is supposed to be the complete account of the actual external world, exactly as it is. It’s most likely impossible to hold something like α, however, similarity relations like P, S1, and S2, are normative concepts that allow for one’s conceptions of the external world to be more or less right, depending on how close to α they are. Maybe it is a mistake to assume that α is something on this chart, but there are still normative concepts that appear to be more similar to experience than others.

Any similarity relation helps narrow down what propositions can be considered normatively true by controlling constants and variables. While there is no single notion of similarity, people have apt ability to understand what similarities are useful for their given purposes. The notion of similarity involved when considering what conceptions of the external world are true results in some difficulties, since something might be considered true for a specific purpose. When one claims that the sun moves from east to west they are making a claim that might have something to do with α, but rather is the way α appears to them. Although it is not necessarily true that the sun moves from east to west, the claim has an epistemic value that is greater than other claims about the world, but less than more accurate conceptions of astrophysics. The claim that the sun goes from east to west is in S1, because it is generally observed that the sun moves in this fashion, but not S2 because it is not objectively true that the sun moves from east to west in all contexts. When a claim falls into S2, there is no way to determine the epistemic value of one belief over another. Some concepts that might fall into this category are Berkeley’s idealism, or any type of Cartesian skepticism. Although every proposition in S2 has a greater epistemic value over propositions the other categories of W, there is no way to determine which proposition has a greater epistemic value without introducing new categories of similarity. By arguing that there are normative concepts, non-genuine relativists imply that there can be propositions that are more similar to α than others. 
Though contemporary relativists often admit that no one can know a proposition completely identical to α, there are normative concepts that appear to apply to α equally well. While none of these normative concepts correlate exactly with anything objective, their similarity to empirical observation is evidence that they are based on objective truths. A true belief might correlate with α, but it will never completely account for α as doing so would be equivalent to omnibenevolence, or a perspective-less perspective. Beliefs are relative in the sense that epistemic propositions are simply possibility claims, but objective in the sense that normative agreement implies that a epistemic proposition applies to α. The apparent lack of objectivity in truth claims extends from how humans only make meaningful claims about any objective world relative to a perspective. There can however, be epistemic propositions that correlate with an objective world more than others. According to an objectivist truth may be relative in a sense, but there is still a sense of an absolute external world that people can make true claims about. One problem with this view, and other objective conceptions of truth, is that it may be impossible to be completely certain whether a fact correlates with belief. The fact that completely certain truth is unattainable except in outlying situations implies that there is an asymptotic relationship between facts and belief in one’s conception of knowledge. People use the concept of knowing as an absolute term, like flatness. 
Something can be relatively flat, as in it is not perfectly flat but close enough for a given purpose. Yet evaluating whether something is flat sometimes forces people to consider how close a surface is to the idea of perfect flatness. Nothing is perfectly flat, however people compare how flat something is to this idea of perfect flatness. This idea of perfect flatness only applies in relative contexts. When considering whether some surface is flat there seems to be an asymptote where perfect flatness should be. One can achieve great degrees of flatness, but a surface that matches the idea of absolute flatness is an unreachable ideal. Knowledge is often used in the same way. People can have ideas that seem generally right and undebatable, however a proposition that perfectly accounts for an objective fact is an unreachable ideal. People can’t be absolutely certain they know something, but we can pretend we do. By having this ideal of a proposition that certainly correlates with objective facts people can easily make and evaluate epistemic propositions. No physical surface is absolutely flat, and no belief is absolutely true, but pretending they can be gives humans the ability to easily express concepts that would otherwise be extremely difficult and time consuming to explain. In this way, when Hales, Prichard, and Carter and Gordon suggest that allowing for normative truths results in epistemic value, they are implying that there are objective facts that propositions can be more or less similar to. Therefore, accounting for epistemic value does not result in the type of genuine epistemic relativism Siegel addresses. 
These theories avoid Siegel’s argument that no proposition can be more or less right by accounting for the relationship between epistemic value, normative truths, and objective facts. This brings up the question of what relativism really means. If relativism is what Siegel, suggests it is then these other relativist claims should be considered more pluralistic that relativistic. Siegel’s definition of relativism, however, is inadequate simply because it is not something one could rationally hold. The conclusion that “everything is relative” might be beneficial for considering other people’s perspectives, but I would be surprised if a rational person seriously held that all views are equally good. It is simply not the case that all views are just as good as each other. For example, it is not the case that curing syphilis by submerging in a mercury vat is just as effective as treating syphilis with medicine. Maybe one can’t know this until they try it out, but there are some things that are just not empirically equivalent. It should be fairly obvious to people who know what mercury is that it shouldn’t be used as syphilis treatment. Genuine epistemic relativism isn’t a realistic view that people hold to the extent that Siegel suggests. The more consistent contemporary theories in this paper offer a conception of relativism that doesn’t include skepticism about an objective world, but they’re still epistemic relativism. These more coherent conceptions of relativism are not genuinely relative. Any relativistic model that accounts for epistemic value cannot be genuinely relative, since failure to account for epistemic value leads to self-referential incoherence. Being an epistemic relativist doesn’t mean that you hold there are no objective truths, rather it has to do with acknowledging the relativity of language and understanding how it relates to one’s own life. A relativist can imply that there are pluralist and objectivist concepts of truth, while still maintaining that humans understand the world in a relative manner. Relative truth should be construed differently. This definition of relativism is like a pluralistic view of truth, but it incorporates the sense of relative truth essential to almost any contemporary relativist theory:
Commensurate Epistemic Relativism: “for any knowledge-claim p, p can be evaluated only in reference to a set of background principles s1 – sN, and given a different set of background principles s’1 – s’N, one can rationally evaluate p based on the coherence of propositions to generally agreed upon normative truths.”


References
Carter, J. A., & Gordon, E. C. (2014). A new maneuver against the epistemic relativist. Synthese, 191(8) 
Darmstadter, H. (2016). Relativism defended. Cogent Arts and Humanities, 3, 1-11. 
Hales, S. D. (2006). Relativism and the foundations of philosophy MIT Press. 
Hales, S. D. (1997). A consistent relativism. Mind, 106(421), 33-52. 
Kölbel, M. (2004). Indexical relativism versus genuine relativism. International Journal of Philosophical Studies, 12(3), 297-313. 
Kripke, S. (1971). Identity and necessity. In J. Kim, D. Korman & E. Sosa (Eds.), Metaphysics:	An anthology (Second ed., pp. 122-140) Wiley-Blackwell Publishing.
Kusch, M. (2017). Epistemic relativism, scepticism, pluralism. Synthese, 194(12), 4687-4703. 
Kvanvig, J. (2003). The Value of Knowledge and the Pursuit of Understanding. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press.
O'Grady, P. (2004). Wittgenstein and relativism. International Journal of Philosophical Studies, 12(3), 315-337. 
Pritchard, D. (2009). Defusing epistemic relativism. Synthese, 166(2), 397-412. 
Pritchard, D. (2009). Knowledge, understanding and epistemic value. Royal Institute of Philosophy Supplement; Roy.Inst.Philos.Suppl., 84(64), 19-43.
Quine, W. V. (1956). Quantifiers and propositional attitudes. The Journal of Philosophy, 53(5), 177-187. 
Siegel, H. (2011). Epistemological relativism: Arguments pro and con. A Companion to Relativism, 201-218. 
Weinberg, J. M. (2007). Moderate epistemic relativism and our epistemic goals. Episteme, 4(1), 66-92.

Website Development Proposal for The Bagel Spot
Prepared by: Alex Bauer
Date: January 27, 2025

Introduction
Thank you for considering working with me for your website development needs. We are excited about the opportunity to work with The Bagel Spot, a local gourmet deli renowned for its delicious offerings and community presence. I aim to create a custom website that enhances your online presence, streamlines your operations, and provides an exceptional experience for your customers.

Project Overview
This proposal outlines a multi-stage plan to develop a comprehensive website for The Bagel Spot. The project includes fundamental setup, progressive enhancements, and the integration of advanced features to support your business objectives.

Scope of Work
Stage 1: Website Fundamentals
1. Domain and SSL Configuration
Domain Setup:
Configure your domain, bagel-spot.com, including DNS settings and domain forwarding.
SSL Certificate Installation:
Install and configure an SSL certificate to secure your website with HTTPS encryption, ensuring data security and building customer trust.
Estimated Cost: $250
2. Email Setup
Professional Email Accounts:
Use a reliable email hosting provider (e.g., Google Workspace, Zoho Mail)  to set up professional email addresses (e.g., info@bagel-spot.com, orders@bagel-spot.com, your-name@bagel-spot.com).
Estimated Cost: $100
3. Temporary Redirection
Interim Redirection:
Redirect your domain to your current ordering platform or Yelp/Google Business listing while the new website is under development.
Included: No additional cost

Stage 2: Basic Information Page
1. Single-Page React Application
Design and Development:
Create an info page that includes essential information about The Bagel Spot.
Estimated Cost: $500
2. Content and Features
Business Information:
Location, operating hours, contact details.
Branding:
Incorporate your logo, color scheme, and imagery to reflect your brand identity.
Call-to-Action (CTA) Buttons:
Direct web traffic to your preferred platforms (e.g., online ordering, social media, Yelp/Google reviews).
Included: No additional cost
3. Hosting
Deployment:
Host the website on a reliable platform such as Heroku with Eco Dynos, ensuring scalability and uptime.
Estimated Cost: $84/year
(Heroku Eco Dynos at $7/month)
4. Responsive Design
Mobile Optimization:
Ensure the website is responsive and accessible on all devices (desktops, tablets, mobile phones).
Included: No additional cost

Stage 3: Multi-Page Static Website
1. Site Expansion
Additional Pages:
Develop multiple static pages to provide comprehensive information.
Home Page
About Us
Menu
Contact Us
FAQs
Testimonials
Estimated Cost: $950
2. Navigation and Usability
Menu Design:
Implement a clean, easy-to-navigate menu using mmenu.js.
Search Functionality:
Enable users to search for menu items or content within the site.
Included: No additional cost
3. Enhanced Features
Visual Appeal:
Use high-quality images, graphics, and animations to enhance user engagement.
SEO Optimization:
Implement basic SEO practices to improve search engine rankings and visibility.
Included: No additional cost

Stage 4: Privatized Online Ordering System
1. Custom Online Ordering Integration
Ordering Platform:
Integrate an online ordering system directly into your website.
Payment Processing:
Connect with payment processors like Square or Clover for secure transactions.
User Accounts:
Allow customers to create accounts, save favorites, and view order history.
App integrations:
Incorporation of popular app elements into your website, including Yelp, Delivery Apps, and Social Media Widgets.
Further opportunities for development in:
Loyalty Programs
Customer Service Enhancements
Inventory Management
Estimated Cost: $2400
2. Cost Efficiency
Reduced Fees:
Eliminate reliance on third-party platforms (e.g., DoorDash, Grubhub), reducing associated fees.
Benefit: Included as part of the integration
3. Security and Compliance
Data Protection:
Ensure all transactions are secure with SSL encryption.
Regulatory Compliance:
Adhere to PCI DSS (Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard) requirements.
Included: No additional cost

Options for E-commerce Solutions
Option 1: Custom-Built Website
As outlined in Stage 4

Option 2: Utilizing Paid Platforms (e.g., Shopify)
Benefits
Quick Setup:
Faster development time with pre-built templates and functionalities.
User-Friendly Management:
Easy for business owners to update and manage content without coding knowledge.
Considerations
Ongoing Costs:
Monthly subscription fees and transaction fees.
Customization Limits:
Less flexibility for custom features compared to a made-from-scratch site.

$800

Support:

Estimated Pricing
Cost Breakdown
Short-Term Focus: If you’re just starting out or need a quick, affordable solution, Shopify (Option 2) is a great choice. It provides all the essentials, and you can always migrate to a custom-built site later as your business grows. It will cost you less to get started but more in fees to run your business.
Long-Term Focus: If you’re looking for a scalable, cost-efficient solution with full customization, a custom-built website (Option 1) is the better option. While the upfront cost is higher, it pays off in the long run with lower transaction fees, no platform dependency, and complete control over your site.

The Normative Influence of Epistemic Value: Reconciling Epistemic Relativism and Objectivism in Contemporary Philosophy
Alexander E. Bauer
Lawrence University
Introduction
The philosophical debate between epistemic relativism and objectivism has long been a central concern in contemporary epistemology. Epistemic relativism challenges the notion of absolute, objective truth by asserting that knowledge and justification are relative to specific cultures, societies, or historical contexts. Objectivism, on the other hand, maintains that there are universal standards of truth and rationality that transcend individual perspectives.
This paper aims to bridge the gap between these seemingly opposing viewpoints by:
Outlining how epistemic incommensurability can motivate Siegel’s conception of genuine relativism.
Demonstrating why Siegel’s arguments against relativism fail to refute contemporary relativistic theories.
Discussing why many modern versions of epistemic relativism imply the existence of an external world.
Ultimately, I argue that consistent relativistic models diverge from Siegel’s conception of relativism, even if they appear similar on the surface. By examining the interplay between relativism and objectivism, we can develop a more nuanced understanding of knowledge that accounts for both the influence of cultural perspectives and the existence of objective facts.
To navigate this complex discussion, several foundational concepts—referred to here as primitive notions—are introduced:
Propositions
Facts
Beliefs
Perspectives (or conceptual schemes)
Epistemic value
Additionally, three types of truth claims are delineated:
Objective truths
Normative truths
Relative truths
Clarifying these concepts is essential for understanding how relativism and objectivism might be reconciled.
Primitive Notions
Propositions
Propositions are the meanings expressed by sentences when interpreted within a language. While sentences can vary across languages, the propositions they convey often maintain a consistent conceptual meaning. In this context, propositions represent the content or claims that can be true or false, independent of the linguistic form used to express them.
For example, the English sentence "Snow is white" and the German sentence "Schnee ist weiß" convey the same proposition. Propositions are essential units in philosophical discussions because they allow us to analyze the content of beliefs and statements without being confined to specific linguistic expressions.
Facts
Facts are necessarily true relationships that exist objectively and externally. They represent the way the world is, independent of our beliefs or perceptions. While propositions can represent facts, they are not identical to the facts themselves. Facts are objective and absolute in character, whereas propositions are the vehicles through which we attempt to capture or describe facts.
In this paper, I am not claiming that any person can know a fact directly; rather, the notion of a fact is important for explaining the distinction between language and external reality. Understanding facts as external and objective allows us to discuss the accuracy or truthfulness of propositions in relation to the world.
Beliefs
Beliefs are intentional states wherein individuals assert that certain propositions correlate with objective facts. Beliefs are how people engage with epistemic propositions—they are commitments to the truth of certain propositions based on one's understanding, evidence, or reasoning.
For instance, if someone believes that "The Earth orbits the Sun," they are asserting that this proposition accurately represents an objective fact about the solar system. Beliefs can be justified or unjustified, true or false, depending on their alignment with facts and the reasoning supporting them.
Perspectives (Conceptual Schemes)
Perspectives, or conceptual schemes, refer to the systems of belief, linguistic frameworks, or sets of categories through which individuals interpret and interact with the world. Every person operates within a perspective that shapes how they understand experiences, form beliefs, and evaluate claims.
When determining whether a belief is justified, we rely on standards or procedures inherent to our conceptual schemes. These standards guide how we differentiate justified beliefs from unjustified ones and influence our reasoning processes.
As Krausz and Meiland note:
"[The notion of a perspective] is so pervasive in our intellectual life that it is a major element in the thinking of philosophers who are in other respects radically different from one another. For example, the neopositivist Rudolf Carnap speaks of linguistic frameworks; the neo-Kantian C.I. Lewis speaks of networks of categories; and the later Wittgenstein talks about forms of life. But they are all talking about conceptual schemes in a broader or narrower sense of that expression." (Krausz and Meiland, 1982, pp. 7–8)
Understanding perspectives is crucial for examining how different individuals or cultures may have varying standards of truth and justification.
Epistemic Value
Epistemic value refers to the degree to which a proposition is considered certain, justified, or valuable from an epistemological standpoint. Within a conceptual scheme, propositions are assigned epistemic value based on how well they correlate with the perspective's standards and objective facts.
Epistemic value allows us to prioritize certain beliefs over others and assess the strength of justifications. Under objectivist epistemology, for example, a justified true belief holds greater epistemic value than a mere belief or a belief that is justified but false.
Types of Truth Claims
Objective Truths
Objective truths are propositions that are necessarily true based on objective facts. They hold universally, regardless of individual perspectives or conceptual schemes. Objective truths are the target of scientific inquiry and rational investigation, aiming to describe the world as it is.
An example of an objective truth is the proposition "Water is H₂O," which reflects the chemical composition of water independent of human perspectives.
Normative Truths
Normative truths are propositions that are generally acknowledged by a group or society to correlate with facts. While they may not be necessarily true in all contexts, they carry significant weight within particular perspectives due to shared standards or values.
Normative truths function as conventions or accepted beliefs that guide behavior and reasoning within a community. For example, "One should tell the truth" is a normative truth in many societies, reflecting shared moral standards.
Relative Truths
Relative truths are propositions that are possibly true within certain contexts or perspectives. Their truth value depends on specific background principles, conceptual schemes, or cultural standards. Different philosophers define relative truth differently, but in this paper, I argue that Siegel’s definition lacks coherence in representing knowledge, whereas alternative conceptions effectively capture the essence of knowledge.
An example of a relative truth is "Spicy food is delicious," which may be true for some individuals or cultures but not for others. Relative truths highlight how beliefs and judgments can vary based on differing perspectives.
This paper will demonstrate that Siegel’s definition of relative truths does not coherently represent knowledge, while alternative conceptions can and do represent knowledge effectively.
1. Epistemic Incommensurability and Siegel’s Genuine Relativism
1.1 Objective Epistemology and Naïve Objectivism
People often make consistent truth claims about objects that, at first glance, appear contradictory. For instance:
Seafarers observe that the sun moves from east to west across the sky—a reliable and helpful truth for navigation.
Astronomers regard the sun as a fixed point at the center of the solar system—a central assumption for heliocentric models.
Astrophysicists note that the sun orbits a massive black hole at the center of the Milky Way galaxy—a fundamental consideration in galactic dynamics.
These statements seem inconsistent: the sun cannot simultaneously be moving, stationary, and orbiting in mutually exclusive ways. However, when considered within their respective contexts and reconciled through a commensurate understanding, these truths can coexist coherently.
The apparent contradictions arise from differing perspectives and levels of analysis:
Contextual Truths: Each statement is true within a specific context or frame of reference. From Earth’s surface, the sun appears to move across the sky due to the Earth's rotation. Within the solar system, the sun is relatively stationary compared to the planets orbiting it. Within the galaxy, the sun itself orbits the galactic center.
Reconciliation: By understanding the underlying mechanisms and frames of reference, we can reconcile these truths and see how they fit together in a broader picture.
Objective epistemology holds that facts are objective and absolute. Under this view, propositions can be evaluated based on their proximity to objective truth. A belief that aligns closely with an objective fact has higher epistemic value than one that does not. This approach captures intuitions about what makes a belief justifiable.
Naïve objectivist conceptual schemes often include the following views:
There are facts: Objective truths exist independently of our beliefs or perceptions.
Example: The Earth orbits the Sun, regardless of whether people believe it or not.
Correspondence to facts: Sentences like "S knows that p" or "S is justified in believing p" are true when they correspond to objective facts.
Example: Scientists are justified in believing that water boils at 100°C at sea level because this corresponds to empirical observations.
Objectivity of facts: Facts are objective and absolute, unaffected by individual perspectives. They are the same for everyone.
Example: The chemical composition of gold is the same worldwide.
Within this model, justified true beliefs hold greater epistemic value than mere beliefs or justified beliefs without truth. The hierarchy of epistemic value under objectivism can be represented as:
Belief: S believes that p.
Justified Belief: S is justified in believing that p.
Justified True Belief: S knows that p because p is true, and S is justified in believing it.
1.2 Relativist Critique and Epistemic Incommensurability
Relativists challenge naïve objectivism by highlighting situations where different perspectives yield conflicting yet valid truths. Instead of reconciling the sun's movement through a single framework, relativists argue that each statement is true within its specific context, and there is no need to subsume them under an absolute truth.
Relativism implies that the function of truth in objective epistemology doesn’t function properly when considering radically different epistemic standards. The relativist critique stems from empirical evidence that individuals and cultures may not share the same standards for judging truth. Cultures can have fundamentally different methods of forming valid conclusions due to varying foundational beliefs, or hinge propositions.
When such differences are radical, they may lead to epistemic incommensurability (EI).
Epistemic Incommensurability (EI): It is possible for two agents to hold opposing beliefs that are rationally justified to an equal extent, with no rational basis by which either agent could persuade the other to revise their view.
Philosophers like Peter Winch support EI with empirical evidence. Winch examines the Azande tribe, who rely on a poison oracle involving the substance benge to make significant decisions. The poison oracle is a central institution in their society:
"At an oracular consultation benge is administered to a fowl, while a question is asked in a form permitting a yes or no answer. The fowl's death or survival is specified beforehand as giving the answer 'yes' or 'no.' The answer is then checked by administering benge to another fowl and asking the question the other way round... The poison oracle is all-pervasive in Zande life and all steps of any importance in a person's life are settled by reference to it." (Winch, 1964, p. 311)
From a Western scientific perspective, using a poison oracle lacks empirical validity. However, Winch argues that one cannot meaningfully criticize the Azande's methods because the concept of validity itself is culturally relative. The Azande have a different conceptual scheme for understanding causality, evidence, and justification.
Winch writes:
"The forms in which rationality expresses itself in the culture of a human society cannot be elucidated simply in terms of the logical coherence of the rules according to which activities are carried out in that society. For... we are not even in a position to determine what is and what is not coherent in such a context of rules, without raising questions about the point which following those rules has in the society." (Winch, 1964, p. 315)
Winch suggests that reality does not inherently provide meaning to language; rather, our language shapes our conception of reality. This view aligns with Wittgenstein's philosophy of language, where meaning is derived from language games and forms of life.
If Winch is correct, EI follows, implying that there is no neutral standpoint from which to evaluate conflicting beliefs. The standards of rationality and justification are internal to each conceptual scheme, making cross-cultural evaluation problematic.
2. Critique of Siegel’s Arguments Against Relativism
2.1 Siegel’s Genuine Epistemic Relativism
Harvey Siegel responds to EI by defining Genuine Epistemic Relativism as follows:
"For any knowledge-claim p, p can be evaluated only in reference to another set of background principles s₁–sₙ, and given a different set of background principles s'₁–s'ₙ, there is no neutral way of choosing between the two or more alternative sets in evaluating p with respect to rational justification." (Siegel, 2011, p. 202)
Under this framework, truth becomes relative to perspectives, leading to the conclusion that all beliefs are equally valid. This resembles Protagorean relativism, where "what seems true to anyone is true for him to whom it seems so." If all truth is relative to individual perspectives, then no belief can be deemed superior to another.
Siegel contends that such relativism makes all epistemic notions equivalent, effectively collapsing the hierarchy of epistemic value:
Belief: S believes that p.
Justified Belief: S is justified in believing that p.
Truth: p is true.
Relative Truth: p is true for S.
Under genuine relativism, these distinctions lose significance because each belief is true relative to the believer's perspective. This leads to a form of skepticism where the notions of truth and rightness become meaningless, and no belief can be defended as better or more justified than another—including epistemic relativism itself.
Siegel argues that genuine relativism is self-referentially incoherent because it lacks epistemic value. If all beliefs are equally valid within their respective perspectives, then the claim "All truth is relative" is itself just another perspective with no special status. Moreover, attempting to defend relativism presupposes some neutral standards of rationality, which contradicts the relativist position.
In his argument, Siegel suggests that relativists face a dilemma:
Accept that some general, non-relative truths exist (A): This contradicts the relativist claim that all truth is relative.
Deny that any general, non-relative truths exist (B): This leads to self-referential incoherence because the relativist cannot claim their position is more correct than any other.
Thus, according to Siegel, genuine epistemic relativism is an indefensible position.
2.2 Contemporary Relativist Responses
Contemporary relativists often reject Siegel's depiction of relativism. Philosophers like Steven Hales, Duncan Pritchard, and Carter and Gordon propose versions of epistemic relativism that account for epistemic value and avoid self-referential incoherence.
2.2.1 Hales’s Consistent Relativism
In "A Consistent Relativism," Steven Hales argues that his version of relativism holds that "everything true is relatively true," rather than "everything is relative." By employing modal logic similar to Saul Kripke's possible worlds framework, Hales demonstrates that relative truth can coexist with notions of necessity and possibility.
Modal Logic and Relative Truth:
Necessity (■): Proposition P is necessarily true if it is true in all possible worlds.
Possibility (◆): Proposition P is possibly true if it is true in at least one possible world.
Hales suggests that if something is relatively necessarily true (◆■P), then it is necessarily true (■P). This implies that relative truths can reflect objective facts, and propositions can have varying degrees of epistemic value based on their alignment with necessity.
He writes:
"It is no more incoherent to relativize the truth of propositions to perspectives given a perspectivist semantics than it is to relativize the truth of propositions to possible worlds given a possible worlds semantics, or to relativize truth to languages given an array of languages... Relativism can be made consistent if truth is relativized to perspectives in the same way that it is relativized to possible worlds in ordinary modal logic." (Hales, 1997, pp. 39–40)
By allowing for necessary truths within a relativistic framework, Hales avoids self-referential incoherence. He maintains that language is necessarily relative but accepts that some propositions can be judged as more accurate or reliable based on their coherence with objective facts.
Epistemic Value in Hales's Relativism:
Hales's relativism allows for propositions to have greater or lesser epistemic value:
Relative Truth: P is true relative to a perspective.
Objective Correlation: The extent to which a relative truth aligns with objective facts increases its epistemic value.
Possibility and Necessity: All necessary truths are relatively true, but not all relatively true propositions are necessary.
By distinguishing between necessary truths and relative truths, Hales preserves the hierarchy of epistemic value and avoids equating all beliefs.
2.2.2 Pritchard’s Dialectical Epistemic Relativism
Duncan Pritchard introduces Dialectical Epistemic Relativism, which acknowledges that while standards of belief justification may vary between frameworks, rational discourse can lead to normative truths. He argues that proposing one's method of belief formation as legitimate implies that it meets certain objective standards of reliability.
Pritchard emphasizes the importance of openness to counterevidence and engagement with other epistemic frameworks:
"Once we recognize that even the holders of well-grounded beliefs by epistemic relativist lights need to be open to counterevidence, including counterevidence offered by those who inhabit different epistemic frameworks, then it becomes clear even the epistemic relativist must allow that there is no epistemic justification for a 'closed' epistemic framework, one that will not countenance engagement with other epistemic frameworks." (Pritchard, 2009, p. 411)
By allowing for debate and the possibility of persuasion, Pritchard's relativism preserves epistemic value and avoids self-referential incoherence. He suggests that even if our foundational principles differ, we can still engage in rational discourse to evaluate beliefs.
Normative Truths and Epistemic Value:
Shared Standards: Through dialogue, individuals can identify shared standards or criteria for evaluating beliefs.
Justification: Beliefs can be justified relative to these normative standards.
Epistemic Improvement: Engagement with diverse perspectives can lead to refinement and improvement of one's epistemic framework.
Pritchard's approach aligns with a form of epistemic pluralism, where multiple perspectives contribute to our understanding of truth.
2.2.3 Carter and Gordon’s Relativism and Understanding
Carter and Gordon focus on the cognitive gain achieved by organizing propositions in a practical way. They argue that while individuals may hold the same objective facts, the way they understand and relate these facts is relative to their perspectives.
Drawing on Jon Kvanvig's observation:
"One can know many unrelated pieces of information, but understanding is achieved only when informational items are pieced together by the subject in question." (Kvanvig, 2003, p. 192)
Carter and Gordon suggest that understanding involves discerning explanatory relationships between propositions—a subjective process. This relativity does not undermine the existence of objective epistemic reasons but highlights the value of diverse perspectives in constructing knowledge.
They write:
"We can grant all of the key data points that [Ian] Hacking takes as motivating the denial of objective epistemic reasons, but we need not accept his conclusion; indeed, we have offered a diagnosis of the data that is compatible with a denial of epistemic relativism. After all, any meta-epistemological commitments (objectivist or otherwise) should allow for individuals to differ in what they know." (Carter and Gordon, 2014, p. 8)
By emphasizing that interpretations are relative while acknowledging the role of objective facts, their approach avoids the issues Siegel raises.
Understanding and Epistemic Value:
Objective Facts: Knowledge is based on objective facts observed through empirical evidence.
Relative Understanding: Individuals organize and relate these facts differently, leading to varied understandings.
Cognitive Gain: Understanding enhances epistemic value by connecting facts in meaningful ways.
Their view supports a relativism that is compatible with objectivism, recognizing that while facts are objective, our comprehension of them is influenced by our perspectives.
3. Contemporary Epistemic Relativism and the External World
3.1 Normative Truths and Epistemic Value
Contemporary relativists accept the existence of objective facts but recognize that our access to these facts is mediated by our perspectives. Normative truths emerge when a group reaches consensus on certain propositions, suggesting that these beliefs likely correlate with objective facts.
Epistemic Value in Relativism:
Alignment with Facts: Beliefs have higher epistemic value when they align closely with objective facts.
Consensus: Normative truths gain credibility through communal agreement and withstand scrutiny over time.
Justification: Beliefs are justified within a framework but can be evaluated based on coherence, empirical support, and explanatory power.
When individuals agree that one belief is better than another, they imply that there is an external reality that their beliefs aim to describe. By accounting for epistemic value and recognizing normative truths, contemporary relativists avoid the skepticism and incoherence associated with Siegel's genuine relativism.
3.2 Similarity Relations and Approximating Objective Truth
Understanding that we may never fully grasp objective facts directly, contemporary relativists utilize similarity relations to approximate truth. By comparing propositions based on their coherence with empirical observations and normative truths, we can judge some beliefs to be more accurate or reliable than others.
Conceptual Model:
W: The set of all possible worlds.
P: The subset of worlds consistent with our understanding of physics (physically possible worlds).
S₁: The subset of worlds accounting for physics and other normative truths.
S₂: The subset of worlds accounting for physics and normative truths that are empirically equivalent.
α: The point representing the complete account of the actual external world.
We may not hold a proposition identical to α, but similarity relations like those in S₁ and S₂ allow us to approximate it. Beliefs within S₁ are more similar to α than those outside it.
Evaluating Epistemic Value:
Empirical Equivalence: Some propositions may be empirically equivalent but differ in theoretical underpinnings (e.g., different interpretations of quantum mechanics).
Coherence: Beliefs that cohere with established theories and observations have higher epistemic value.
Refinement: Ongoing inquiry and evidence allow us to refine our beliefs and move closer to α.
Even when empirical equivalence prevents us from determining the epistemic value of mutually inconsistent concepts within S₂, similarity relations help us navigate toward objective truth.
3.3 Reconciling Relativism and Objectivism
By integrating the recognition of objective facts with an understanding of the relative nature of language and perspectives, contemporary relativists offer a reconciled view that combines elements of both relativism and objectivism.
Key Points of Reconciliation:
Objective Facts Exist: There is an external reality that our beliefs aim to describe.
Perspectives Mediate Understanding: Our access to objective facts is mediated by conceptual schemes and perspectives.
Epistemic Value Guides Evaluation: Beliefs can be evaluated based on their epistemic value, which considers coherence, empirical support, and normative consensus.
Openness to Revision: Recognizing the limitations of our perspectives encourages openness to new evidence and alternative viewpoints.
This approach acknowledges that while our beliefs are relative in the sense that they are formed within perspectives, they can still approximate objective truths. Just as a surface can be considered "flat" for practical purposes, even if it is not perfectly flat at the microscopic level, our beliefs can be considered "true" insofar as they effectively correspond to objective facts.
Therefore, accounting for epistemic value does not result in the type of genuine relativism Siegel criticizes. Instead, a more accurate definition of relativism emerges:
Commensurate Epistemic Relativism:
"For any knowledge claim p, p can be evaluated only in reference to a set of background principles s₁–sₙ. Given different sets of background principles s'₁–s'ₙ, one can rationally evaluate p based on the coherence of propositions with generally agreed-upon normative truths."
This definition allows for the assessment of beliefs based on epistemic value, avoiding self-referential incoherence and acknowledging the influence of both relativism and objectivism.
4. Addressing Empirical Equivalence and Skepticism
4.1 Empirical Equivalence and Underdetermination
A challenge arises when empirical evidence equally supports multiple, mutually inconsistent theories—a situation known as empirical equivalence. In such cases, rational evaluation based solely on empirical data may not determine which theory is superior.
Examples of Empirical Equivalence:
Scientific Theories: The Copenhagen interpretation and the many-worlds interpretation of quantum mechanics are empirically equivalent but offer different ontological commitments.
Philosophical Positions: Realism and instrumentalism in science can make the same predictions while differing on the existence of unobservable entities.
4.2 Overcoming Skepticism
Empirical equivalence can lead to skepticism about our ability to know the external world. However, contemporary relativists address this by:
Emphasizing Coherence: Preferring theories that offer greater explanatory coherence and simplicity (Occam's Razor).
Considering Practical Utility: Evaluating theories based on their predictive power and usefulness in applications.
Engaging in Meta-Theoretical Analysis: Assessing underlying assumptions, theoretical virtues, and broader implications.
By integrating these considerations, we can make rational choices between empirically equivalent theories, acknowledging that our selection is informed by normative standards within our epistemic community.
5. The Role of Language and Communication
5.1 Relativity of Language
Language plays a crucial role in shaping our conceptual schemes. The relativist recognizes that:
Meaning is Contextual: Words and sentences derive meaning from their usage within a language community.
Translation and Interpretation: Exact translation between languages or conceptual schemes may be impossible due to differing underlying structures (Quine's indeterminacy of translation).
5.2 Communication Across Perspectives
Despite linguistic and conceptual differences, communication and understanding across perspectives are possible through:
Shared Experiences: Common human experiences provide a foundation for mutual understanding.
Analogies and Metaphors: These tools bridge gaps between conceptual schemes.
Incremental Learning: Exposure to alternative perspectives broadens one's conceptual repertoire.
By engaging in cross-perspective communication, individuals can expand their own conceptual schemes and enhance their understanding of the world.
Conclusion
The interplay between epistemic relativism and objectivism presents a nuanced landscape of philosophical inquiry. Harvey Siegel's genuine relativism, which denies the possibility of neutral evaluation and collapses epistemic value, fails to accurately represent the positions of contemporary relativists. By accounting for epistemic value and recognizing normative truths, modern relativistic theories imply the existence of an external world and allow for rational evaluation of beliefs.
Philosophers like Steven Hales, Duncan Pritchard, and Carter and Gordon demonstrate that it is possible to acknowledge the relative nature of language and perspectives while maintaining a commitment to objective facts. They argue that our access to truth is mediated by our conceptual schemes but emphasize that this does not preclude the existence of objective truths or the pursuit of knowledge.
By integrating the recognition of objective facts with an understanding of the relative nature of our perspectives, contemporary relativists offer a reconciled view that combines elements of both relativism and objectivism. This approach preserves the meaningfulness of philosophical discourse, supports the evaluation of epistemic claims based on their merits, and underscores the importance of striving toward objective truth—even when certainty remains elusive.
In embracing this integrated perspective, we acknowledge the complexity of human understanding and the necessity of engaging with diverse viewpoints. By fostering open dialogue and remaining receptive to new evidence, we can navigate the challenges posed by epistemic incommensurability and work collaboratively toward a more nuanced and comprehensive understanding of the world.

Business Analyst Role Overview: A Business Analyst bridges the gap between business needs and technical solutions by analyzing processes, gathering requirements, and ensuring successful project delivery.
Key Responsibilities: Gathering and documenting business requirements. Analyzing and improving business processes. Communicating with stakeholders to identify needs and align objectives. Creating detailed project documentation such as BRDs, FRDs, and use cases. Supporting project management and ensuring timely delivery. Collaborating with technical teams to design solutions. Conducting data analysis to inform decision-making.
Key Skills for a Business Analyst:
Technical Skills: Data Analysis (Excel, SQL, Power BI, Tableau), Process Modeling (BPMN, UML), Requirement Gathering and Documentation, Knowledge of SDLC (Waterfall, Agile, Scrum), Wireframing and Prototyping (Balsamiq, Axure, Figma), Software Testing (UAT, Functional Testing).
Soft Skills: Communication and Stakeholder Management, Critical Thinking and Problem-Solving, Time Management and Prioritization, Negotiation and Conflict Resolution.
Tools Commonly Used by Business Analysts: Requirement Management: JIRA, Confluence, Trello, Microsoft Visio. Data Analysis: Excel, SQL, Power BI, Tableau, R, Python. Collaboration: Slack, Microsoft Teams, Google Workspace. Prototyping and Wireframing: Axure, Balsamiq, Figma, Adobe XD. Documentation: Microsoft Office Suite, Google Docs, SharePoint.
Common Interview Questions and Example Answers:
Can you explain the role of a Business Analyst in a project? Answer: The Business Analyst acts as the intermediary between stakeholders and the technical team. My role involves understanding business needs, gathering and documenting requirements, analyzing processes, and ensuring the final solution meets the business objectives. I work closely with stakeholders to clarify goals and collaborate with the technical team to design solutions that align with those goals.
How do you approach gathering requirements from stakeholders? Answer: I use a combination of techniques such as interviews, workshops, surveys, and observation to gather requirements. I also create use cases and user stories to ensure I capture both functional and non-functional requirements. Clear communication and asking the right questions are key to understanding stakeholder needs.
How do you handle conflicting requirements from stakeholders? Answer: When conflicts arise, I prioritize understanding the underlying business goals. I facilitate discussions between stakeholders to identify the root cause of the conflict and suggest compromises or alternative solutions. If necessary, I escalate the issue to the project sponsor for resolution while ensuring transparency and alignment with the project objectives.
What techniques do you use for process improvement? Answer: I use techniques like process mapping, root cause analysis, and gap analysis to identify inefficiencies. I also employ Six Sigma principles and BPMN to redesign processes and ensure they align with business objectives. By leveraging tools like Visio or Lucidchart, I create visual representations of the improved processes.
Describe a challenging project you worked on and how you handled it. Answer: In a previous project, I faced challenges aligning stakeholders with varying priorities. I organized a series of workshops to clarify objectives, facilitated discussions to address concerns, and used data-driven insights to support recommendations. By maintaining open communication and focusing on shared goals, I successfully delivered the project on time.
Technical Questions for Business Analyst:
What is the difference between functional and non-functional requirements? Answer: Functional requirements define what the system should do, such as specific features or functionalities. Non-functional requirements specify how the system should perform, such as performance, scalability, and security.
What is a use case, and how do you create one? Answer: A use case is a detailed description of how a user interacts with a system to achieve a specific goal. To create one, I identify the actors, define the goal, outline the steps involved, and document any exceptions or alternate flows. This helps ensure the system meets user needs.
Explain the Agile methodology and your experience with it. Answer: Agile is an iterative approach to project management and software development that focuses on delivering small, incremental changes. I have experience working in Agile environments, where I collaborated with cross-functional teams, wrote user stories, participated in sprint planning, and facilitated daily stand-ups to ensure alignment.
Scenario-Based Questions:
How would you handle a situation where the delivered solution does not meet business needs? Answer: I would first analyze the gaps between the delivered solution and the requirements. Then, I would collaborate with the technical team to identify the root cause, whether it’s a miscommunication, scope creep, or a technical limitation. I’d work with stakeholders to prioritize the necessary changes and ensure the solution aligns with their needs.
How would you prioritize requirements in a project? Answer: I use prioritization techniques like MoSCoW (Must Have, Should Have, Could Have, Won’t Have) or weighted scoring models. I also consider factors like business value, urgency, and technical feasibility. Engaging stakeholders in the prioritization process ensures alignment and clarity.
Key Business Analyst Deliverables: Business Requirements Document (BRD), Functional Requirements Document (FRD), Use Cases and User Stories, Process Flow Diagrams, Gap Analysis Reports, Wireframes and Prototypes, Test Cases and UAT Plans, Data Analysis Reports.
Industry-Specific Knowledge: Familiarity with financial, healthcare, retail, or technology domains depending on the role. Understanding of compliance standards like GDPR, HIPAA, or PCI-DSS. Knowledge of ERP and CRM systems such as SAP and Salesforce.

Describe a time when you went above and beyond to assist your team.

Education:

Key Responsibilities:  
Monitoring and analyzing security systems to detect and respond to threats.  
Implementing and maintaining cybersecurity policies and protocols.

Investigating security breaches and conducting forensic analysis.  
Configuring and managing security tools such as firewalls, SIEM, and antivirus software.  
Providing training and awareness programs for employees on cybersecurity best practices.  
Collaborating with IT teams to ensure secure system architecture.  
Ensuring compliance with regulatory and industry standards.  
Developing and testing incident response and disaster recovery plans.  

Key Skills for Cybersecurity Professionals:  
Technical Skills: Proficiency in SIEM tools (e.g., Splunk, QRadar), firewalls, IDS/IPS, vulnerability scanners (e.g., Nessus, Qualys), scripting languages (Python, Bash), and encryption technologies.  
Soft Skills: Analytical thinking, problem-solving, attention to detail, communication, adaptability, and teamwork.  

Common Tools Used by Cybersecurity Professionals:  
SIEM: Splunk, QRadar, LogRhythm.  
Vulnerability Scanners: Nessus, Qualys, OpenVAS.  
Endpoint Security: CrowdStrike, Symantec, McAfee.  
Firewalls: Palo Alto, Fortinet, Cisco ASA.  
Penetration Testing: Metasploit, Burp Suite, Kali Linux.  
Encryption: OpenSSL, GPG, BitLocker.  

Common Interview Questions and Example Answers:  

Can you describe your experience with monitoring and responding to security threats?  
Answer: In my previous role, I used SIEM tools like Splunk to monitor network activity and detect anomalies. For example, I identified a brute-force attack on a server and responded by blocking the offending IP addresses and implementing account lockout policies to prevent further attempts.  

How do you stay updated on the latest cybersecurity threats?  
Answer: I regularly follow cybersecurity blogs, forums, and news sources like Krebs on Security and ThreatPost. I also participate in online communities such as Reddit’s r/cybersecurity and attend webinars and conferences to stay informed about emerging threats and best practices.  

What steps do you take to conduct a vulnerability assessment?  
Answer: I start by identifying the scope of the assessment and gathering system information. I then use tools like Nessus or Qualys to scan for vulnerabilities. After analyzing the results, I prioritize vulnerabilities based on their severity and provide recommendations for remediation.  

Describe a time when you had to handle a security breach.  
Answer: In a previous role, I detected unusual outbound traffic from a workstation, indicating a possible malware infection. I isolated the system from the network, conducted a forensic analysis to identify the malware, and removed it. I then reviewed logs to determine how the malware entered and implemented additional security measures to prevent future incidents.  

How do you ensure compliance with regulatory standards?  
Answer: I conduct regular audits to ensure systems and processes align with standards like GDPR, HIPAA, or PCI-DSS. I also collaborate with legal and compliance teams to stay updated on regulatory changes and provide training to employees to maintain compliance.  

What is your experience with penetration testing?  
Answer: I have performed penetration tests using tools like Metasploit and Burp Suite. For example, I conducted a test on a web application and discovered an SQL injection vulnerability. I reported the issue to the development team and worked with them to implement a fix.  

Technical Questions for Cybersecurity Professionals:  

What is the difference between symmetric and asymmetric encryption?  
Answer: Symmetric encryption uses the same key for both encryption and decryption, making it faster but requiring secure key sharing. Asymmetric encryption uses a public key for encryption and a private key for decryption, providing more security for key exchange but at a slower speed.  

What is a man-in-the-middle attack, and how do you prevent it?  
Answer: A man-in-the-middle attack occurs when an attacker intercepts communication between two parties. To prevent it, I use encryption protocols like TLS, implement strong authentication methods, and educate users about avoiding unsecured networks.  

What is the CIA triad in cybersecurity?  
Answer: The CIA triad stands for Confidentiality, Integrity, and Availability. Confidentiality ensures data is accessible only to authorized users, integrity ensures data is accurate and unaltered, and availability ensures systems and data are accessible when needed.  

Scenario-Based Questions:  

How would you handle a ransomware attack?  
Answer: I would immediately isolate the affected systems to prevent the ransomware from spreading. I would then investigate the attack to determine its scope and identify the ransomware variant. If backups are available, I would restore the affected systems and review security measures to prevent future incidents.  

What would you do if an employee reported a phishing email?  
Answer: I would thank the employee for reporting the email and analyze it to determine if it poses a threat. If it’s malicious, I would block the sender, update email filters, and notify other employees to remain vigilant. I would also use the incident as an opportunity for further security awareness training.  

How would you secure a company’s remote workforce?  
Answer: I would implement VPNs for secure connections, enforce multi-factor authentication (MFA), and ensure all devices have updated antivirus software. I would also provide training on recognizing phishing attempts and avoiding public Wi-Fi.  

Key Deliverables for Cybersecurity Professionals:  
Secure and monitored IT infrastructure.  
Timely detection and response to security incidents.  
Comprehensive vulnerability assessments and remediation plans.  
Effective training programs for employees on cybersecurity best practices.  
Compliance with regulatory and industry standards.  
Documented incident response and recovery procedures.  
Collaborative efforts with IT teams to design secure systems and networks.

I studied philosophy, biology, and computer science in college, and I am particularly fascinated by the intersection of these fields. At first glance, these disciplines might seem disparate, but they converge in profound and thought-provoking ways. Biology provides the foundation of life’s mechanisms, philosophy explores the underlying principles and meaning behind those mechanisms, and computer science offers tools and frameworks for modeling and understanding them. For example, consider the process of transcription and translation in molecular biology. This is a perfect example of recursion and information processing in nature. DNA, essentially a biological code, is transcribed into RNA, which is then translated into proteins—the building blocks of life. This process is not unlike how a computer compiles code, turning abstract instructions into tangible outputs. It’s an elegant recursive system where information flows and transforms across layers, and it raises philosophical questions about the nature of information itself. Is DNA merely a blueprint, or is it something more—a form of biological epistemology, a way for life to "know" itself and adapt to its environment?

Similarly, I am captivated by the concept of figure/ground relationships, which originated in Gestalt psychology but can be applied across disciplines. In philosophy, it’s a way of understanding how we perceive reality—how we distinguish objects from their background, or ideas from the context in which they arise. In biology, this concept manifests in ecosystems, where the "figure" might be a keystone species like bees, and the "ground" is the broader environment that supports and is influenced by them. In computer science, figure/ground relationships appear in user interface design, where clarity and functionality depend on how well the foreground (the user’s focus) is distinguished from the background. These parallels highlight the interconnectedness of seemingly unrelated fields and underscore the importance of interdisciplinary thinking.

Recursion, another fascinating concept, is not just a computational tool but a fundamental principle of life and thought. Recursive patterns are everywhere in nature, from the fractal branching of trees and rivers to the self-replicating loops of DNA. In philosophy, recursion is central to epistemology—the study of knowledge. How do we know what we know? Often, it’s through iterative processes of questioning and refining our understanding. This mirrors the trial-and-error loops in computer algorithms or the feedback systems in biological organisms. Recursion is a reminder that complexity often arises from simple, repeated actions, a principle that applies as much to life as it does to code.

Epistemology, the study of knowledge and how we come to understand the world, ties all these threads together. In philosophy, it challenges us to think about the limits of human understanding and the frameworks we use to interpret reality. In biology, epistemology is embedded in the scientific method and the way organisms themselves "know" their environments through sensory input and adaptation. In computer science, it’s about how machines learn and process information, raising ethical and philosophical questions about artificial intelligence and the nature of consciousness. These intersections are endlessly fascinating to me because they demonstrate that life, in all its forms, is a process of learning, adapting, and evolving.

I was born in Colorado Springs, surrounded by the majestic Rocky Mountains. Growing up in such an environment instilled in me a deep appreciation for nature and the outdoors. I became an advanced skier and volunteered as a ski patroller in high school, which taught me the importance of teamwork, quick decision-making, and staying calm under pressure. My love for the mountains extended to hiking and backpacking, where I found peace and inspiration in the vastness of the wilderness. However, my experiences are not limited to the Rockies. I’ve also lived in Wisconsin and New Orleans, and I currently reside in Michigan. Each of these places has shaped my perspective and deepened my appreciation for the diversity of landscapes and ecosystems. The Great Lakes, with their immense power and beauty, are just as awe-inspiring as the mountains, and the Mississippi River basin is a testament to the interconnectedness of life and water.

My interest in botany stems from this love of nature. Plants are not just passive components of ecosystems; they are active participants that shape and sustain life. I was fortunate to be part of a non-profit organization called BYOBeez (article can be found at: https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0281468), which focused on building artificial beehives for native, non-stinging bees. This experience opened my eyes to the intricate relationships between plants, pollinators, and the broader environment. Bees, for example, are essential for the reproduction of many plants, which in turn support countless other species. By studying these interactions, I gained a deeper understanding of how life is interconnected and how small changes in one part of an ecosystem can ripple across the whole. It’s a reminder of the delicate balance that sustains life and the importance of protecting it.

Life is endlessly fascinating because it operates on so many levels simultaneously. At the molecular level, it’s a dance of atoms and molecules following the laws of chemistry and physics. At the organismal level, it’s a story of adaptation, survival, and reproduction. At the ecosystem level, it’s a web of interactions and dependencies that create stability and resilience. And at the philosophical level, it’s a quest to understand what it all means. These layers are not separate but interconnected, like the threads of a tapestry. Whether we’re studying the behavior of bees, the structure of DNA, or the principles of recursion, we’re exploring the same fundamental question: What is life, and how does it work?
