The Normative Influence of Epistemic Value Part 1: 
How Epistemic Relativism and Objectivism are Conjoined in Contemporary Philosophy.
Alexander E. Bauer
Lawrence University
This paper will (1) Outline how epistemic incommensurability can motivate Siegel’s genuine relativism, (2) show why Siegel’s arguments against relativism fails to refute contemporary relativistic theories, and (3) discuss why many contemporary versions of epistemic relativism imply the existence of an external world. These sections will ultimately argue that any consistent relativistic model does not follow Siegel’s conception of relativism, even though they may appear to be the same. This argument relies on several important primitive notions. These are concepts that may have plenty of synonyms, especially in philosophical disputes. The purpose of this first paragraph is simply to introduce these notions so they can be explained throughout the paper. The first primitive notion is a proposition. Sentences when interpreted have a conceptual meaning. Meanings of sentences are often consistent across languages. Sentences express propositional attitudes that can be expressed in many languages. In this paper, the meaning expressed by a sentence is a proposition, and is essentially equivalent to a concept or claim. The second primitive notion for this paper is a fact. A fact is a necessarily true relationship. Propositions can represent facts, but facts are objective, external, and not identical to the propositions that may represent them. I’m not claiming that any person can know a fact directly, but rather the notion is important for explaining the distinction between language and external facts. The third primitive notion is a belief. A belief is an intentional state where one means that some proposition correlates with an objective fact. Beliefs are how people engage with epistemic propositions. The fourth primitive notion is a perspective, or conceptual scheme. Every perspective has a different system of belief or linguistic framework that is essential for understanding and interacting with the world. When determining whether any belief is justiﬁed, we always rely on some standards or procedures that separate justiﬁed from unjustiﬁed convictions. These standards, in conjunction with relevant information determine epistemic beliefs. Michael Krausz and Jack W. Meiland write: “[The notion of a perspective] is so pervasive in our intellectual life that it is a major element in the thinking of philosophers who are in other respects radically different from one another. For example, the neopositivist Rudolf Carnap speaks of linguistic frameworks; the neo-Kantian C.I. Lewis speaks of networks of categories; and the later Wittgenstein talks about forms of life. But they are all talking about conceptual schemes in a broader or narrower sense of that expression.” (Krausz and Meiland 1982, editors’ introduction, pp. 7–8) The Fifth primitive notion is epistemic value. Conceptual schemes will put value on propositions that correlate with a perspective or objective fact. This judgement of certainty is the epistemic value of a proposition. Additionally, I discuss 3 types of truth claims. Objective truths are necessarily true propositions based on facts. Normative Truths are possibly true propositions that are generally acknowledged to correlate with a fact by a group. Finally, there are relative truths which are just possibly true propositions, although different philosophers define relative truth differently. This paper will show that Siegel’s definition of relative truths does not coherently represent knowledge, while other conceptions of relative truth can and do represent knowledge effectively.
1:         People make consistent truth claims about objects that vary in seemingly contradictory ways (although I’m certain very few people makes this mistake). While seafaring, the fact that the sun moves from east to west across the sky can be a reliable and helpful truth. When one is sending a rocket to the moon, the fact that the sun is at a fixed point in the center of the solar system is a reliable and helpful truth. When one is considering the relationship between our solar system and other nearby stars, the fact that the sun is orbiting around a massive blackhole is a reliable and helpful truth. These ideas are inconsistent with each other on their own. It is not the case that the sun is simultaneously at a fixed point, moving, and orbiting, as those concepts exclude each other. Rather, the truths can be considered all together in a commensurate manner to consistently account for all three. In each case, statements about the sun in one context conflict with the statements in other contexts. Yet, one can explain the sun moving across the sky in terms of earths orbit and rotation, and the suns position in space in terms of it orbiting a black hole. This is not a serious problem for most people, because they understand these truths in a commensurate manner. It’s certainly possible to explain why a truth might seem true considering apparent evidence, but a naive conception of truth can have trouble accounting for apparent conflicts of consistent truth claims. Objectivists argue that these apparently contradictory sentences can be accounted for, yet objective epistemology implies that facts are objective and absolute in character. If this is true, either all observed phenomena can be explained in a commensurate manner, or the truths considered are not truly objective. Objective conceptions of truth imply that sentences of the form “S is justified in believing p” suggest p is more likely to be true considering S’s justification, than “S believes that p. In this way “S is justified in believing p”, has a greater epistemic value (is more correct) than simply “S believes p.” objective epistemology captures intuitions about what makes a belief justifiable. Naïve objective conceptual schemes often consist of the following views:
(1) There are facts.
(2) Sentences like “S knows that p” and “S is justified in believing” are, when true, true in virtue of facts. 
(3) Facts are objective and absolute in character.
Within a model that uses objective principles, different propositions can be closer to the truth than others. Objective conceptual schemes will put value on propositions that correlate with a perspective or objective fact. This judgement of certainty is an essential function of truth concepts. Under objective epistemology, a justified true belief has a greater epistemic value than a justified belief, while a justified belief has a greater epistemic value than just a belief. The naïve objectivist conception of truth maximizes epistemic value because there is a range of how correct an epistemic claim can be. This view of knowledge has been criticized for thousands of years, however, it is still held today because it seems to fit the way people naturally think about knowing. One type of criticism of this naïve objectivism stems from the example above. Instead of trying to commensurate the fact that the sun moves, is at a fixed point, and orbiting, relativists hold that each of these claims is true in a specific context. It is true that the sun moves, when you’re looking at the position of the sun from earth over time. It is true that the earth is at a fixed point, if you’re considering just the solar system. It is true that the earth is orbiting, if you’re considering its position in the Milky Way. Relativists claim that all of these statements can be true at the same time without a commensurate understanding of the sun’s movements. It doesn’t matter whether or not the concepts are mutually exclusive, as long as the concepts are useful. Relativism implies that the function of truth in objective epistemology doesn’t function properly when considering radically different epistemic standards.
This type of criticism of objectivist epistemology stems from empirical evidence that two people may not have the same standards for judging truth in their conceptual scheme. Any conceptual scheme is based on propositions that can vary significantly across different cultures. Cultures sometimes have fundamentally different methods of reaching a valid conclusion because their hinge propositions vary so much that logical arguments are not relevant. If it is possible for two agents to be committed to a radically different set of hinge propositions, there may be grounds to accept epistemic incommensurability. 
Epistemic incommensurability (EI): It is possible for two agents to have opposing beliefs which are rationally justified to an equal extent where there is no rational basis by which either agent could properly persuade the other to revise their view.
Philosophers like Winch propose that there is empirical evidence that EI limits interactions between radically different cultures. These philosophers suggest that the rational basis of indigenous tribes and western culture are based on radically different sets of hinge propositions. Winch writes about the Azande tribe in Africa. This indigenous tribe has a fundamental concept of validity that varies from a western concept of validity so much that the two conceptual schemes are irreconcilable. The Azande’s fundamental difference in the concept of validity originates from the function of a poison oracle in their society. This individual administers a poisonous substance called benge to a fowl. Winch writes that:
“At an oracular consultation benge is administered to a fowl, while a question is asked in a form permitting a yes or no answer. The fowl's death or survival is specified beforehand as giving the answer "yes" or “no” answer is then checked by administering benge to another fowl and asking the question the other way round… The poison oracle is all-pervasive in Zande life and all steps of any importance in a person's life are settled by reference to it.” (Winch, 1964, p. 311)
Indigenous tribes like the Azande accept magic in a way that is inconsistent with western scientific theory. Administering benge to a fowl is not considered a valid and reliable means to reach a conclusion in western scientific theory. However, Winch argues that one could not meaningfully criticize the Azande for reaching conclusions with a poison oracle. For Winch the irreconcilability of the concept of validity means that language is inherently relative. If people agree to a standard form of a valid conclusion they can meaningfully argue, but if they don’t agree on what it means for a claim to be valid there can be no neutral way to decide which conceptual scheme is more correct. Winch writes:
“the forms in which rationality expresses itself in the culture of a human society cannot be elucidated simply in terms of the logical coherence of the rules according to which activities are carried out in that society. For, as we have seen, there comes a point where we are not even in a position to determine what is and what is not coherent in such a context of rules, without raising questions about the point which following those rules has in the society.” (Winch, 1964, p. 315)
Winch and other relativists claim that reality is not what gives language sense. What is real and what is unreal shows itself in a language because the concept of agreement with reality itself belongs to our language. If winch is correct that we are not in a position to determine what is and isn’t not coherent in certain contexts of rules, the EI thesis follows. 
2:        The EI thesis implies that the truth of a sentence P is dependent on some independent factor (like a concept of validity, or conceptual scheme). This principle attributes truth to a proposition only in relation to a specific context. In his paper Epistemic Relativism: Pros and Cons Siegel claims that the relativist conception of truth can be generalized as:
Genuine Epistemic Relativism (Siegel): “for any knowledge-claim p, p can be evaluated only in reference to another set of background principles s1 – sN, and given a different set of background principles s’1 – s’N, there is no neutral way of choosing between the two or more alternative sets in evaluating p with respect to rational justification.” (Siegel, 2011, p. 202)
Since the truth of P is dependent on additional factors, there cannot be a truth that is not relative. Genuine epistemic relativism essentially makes the epistemic value of any two sentences equal. This form of relativism is similar to Protagorean relativism. Reliance on background principles implies that “what seems true to anyone is true for him whom it seems so.” Protagorean relativism suggests that all truth is relative, and epistemic value has no meaning. Siegel’s definition of relativism does not apply to most contemporary forms of relativism, which I will argue for throughout the rest of this paper. If the epistemic value of a belief is not significant then no literal claim can be justifiably proved to be true or false, including epistemological relativism. If a belief cannot be sincerely judged the notions of truth and rightness are essentially meaningless. Objective conceptions of truth suggest that the claim “p is a true belief of S” is more valid than “S is justified in believing p,” which is more valid than just “S believes p.”
(S believes p) < (S is justified in believing p) < (p is true)
Siegel claims that relative conceptions of truth suggest that the claim p is true for S, or p is relatively true is more valid than S believes p, but less valid than p is true. Genuine relativism motivates a specific type of skepticism by equating truth conditions with justification conditions. Since all it takes for something to be true is that someone thinks its true, all epistemic notions become essentially equivalent because they can be understood as ‘p is true for S.’
(S believes p) = (S is justified in believing p) = (p is true) = (p is true for S)
If true beliefs are only true from a perspective, all beliefs that are true in some perspective are just as correct as any other belief. If people do not share a perspective, there is no reasonable way to determine which claims have a greater epistemic value. Genuine epistemic relativism essentially makes all judgements of rightness have an equal epistemic value, which means no view is better than another. Genuine relativism implies that there is no such thing as a necessary truth, something that is true in all relative perspectives. Siegel suggests that relativism redefines the concept of truth to have essentially no function, which means that an objective conception of truth is more practical than a relative model.
In Epistemic Relativism: Pros and Cons, Siegel argues that any model follows the general form of (p is true for S) is self-referentially incoherent because they lack epistemic value. Siegel argument suggests that all types of relativism are indefensible positions.
relativistic truth follows the general form of (p is true for S).
any account of truth that follows the general form of (p is true for S) has no epistemic value.
any account of truth that has no epistemic value is self-referentially incoherent and cannot be defended.
According to this argument, relativists cannot defend the notion of relative truth considering absolutist views, or defend any particular relative truth p as in any way superior to any arbitrary relative truth q. Any defense of a relativist model suggests that there are neutral standards to judge between epistemic claims, and that one view can be more correct than another. If epistemic claims cannot have value whatsoever, then it’s impossible to have philosophical disputes if every position is equally valid. Siegel argues that many contemporary relativist theories are self-referentially incoherent because they rely on a conception of truth that follows the general form of (p is true for S). Siegel argues in Episemic relativism: Pros and Cons that the philosopher Hales commits to relative truth in a way that makes his position self-referentially incoherent. While Siegel argues that Hales’ relativism is self-referentially incoherent, it accounts for epistemic value in a way that avoids Siegel’s arguments.
Hales in his paper A Consistent Relativism, introduces Kripke’s modal operators in a way that is more agreeable to discussing relativism. These operators function in the same way as Kripke’s modal operators but are explained in slightly different terms. For the purposes of this paper, a possible world refers to a relevant subset of the domain of discourse. When someone has a belief, they tend to endorse the idea of a necessary truth consistent with modal logic. In Kripke’s modal logic, there is an idea of necessary truth. If it is necessary that P, P is true of the objective world. This principle is represented by the operator :

If it is not necessary that p is false, then p is possible. This principle is dependent on an idea of necessary truth, but is represented by the operator ◇: 
◇, where w represents a relevant context within a domain of discourse.

These modal operators are essentially identical to the following modal operators used by Hales. If it is objectively true that P, P is true of the objective world. This principle is represented by the operator :

, where α represents an objective world.

If it is not necessary that p is false, then p is possible. This principle is dependent on an idea of necessary truth, but is represented by the operator ◆:

◆, where w represents a relevant context within a domain of discourse.

, If something is not absolutely false it is relatively true. 

The claims that “p is possibly true” and “p is relatively true” are identical under this conception of modal operators. For something to be possibly true, one must be able to accept the necessary premises for the conclusion to follow (a relevant context of the domain of discourse). Likewise, something is relatively true if one can accept the necessary premises for the conclusion to follow. Both concepts rely on related information to determine whether a statement is true or not. While modal operators are sometimes used in different ways especially in respect to possible worlds, Hales tries to make it clear that when someone considers a possible truth, they are simply stating some necessary conditions for a specific conclusion to follow. This is the same idea used in relative truth. When someone considers a relative truth, they are simply contemplating what has to be true for a conclusion to follow. The necessary conditions for a belief might be empirical evidence, but could be any valid premise. If one is committed to using only relative truth, it seems like they imply that there are no necessary truths. Hales argues that this is not the case, even if all human conceptions of truth are relative. The idea that if something is relatively true, it simply must follow from its premises seems to imply Protagorean relativism. Since there is only relative truth Siegel claims that Hales commits to a claim like “what seems true to anyone is true for him whom it seems so.” However, if “what seems true to anyone is true for him whom it seems so,” then no literal claim can be justifiably proved to be true or false, including epistemological relativism itself. Siegel argues that any relativistic claims cannot be justifiably proved to be true under its own background principles. If a belief cannot be sincerely judged the notions of truth and rightness are essentially meaningless. Relativists must presuppose A and B in order to defend epistemic relativism:
A] , a general non-relative view of truth/justification, and hold that a relative view is superior to the general view.
B] ¬, deny that there can be a general non-relative view.
A → ¬B
⊥ If A then one general view of knowledge is epistemically superior to another. (¬B)
B → ¬A
⊥ If B then relativism cannot be epistemically superior to its rivals. (¬A)
	
This contradiction only arises because Siegel’s definition of relativism requires that there cannot be a general, non-relative view of the world. Most serious contemporary work in relativism, however, consists of views that claim that there cannot be a non-relative view of the world, but allow for general conceptions of truth. Siegel’s genuine relativism necessitates the lack of epistemic value, yet relative truth must account for some sense of epistemic value in order to be consistent. 
The next section will discuss how different philosophers distinguish their conceptions of epistemic value from genuine relativism. In this section, this paper will evaluate Siegel’s definition of genuine epistemic relativism in relation to a variety of contemporary relativist theories, which I will distinguish from genuine epistemic relativism by author. The first position is outlined by Hales in his paper, A Consistent Relativism. Contrary to what Siegel argues, Hales claims that his version of epistemic relativism is consistent because his version of relativism argues for the claim that everything true is relatively true, rather than everything is relative like Siegel’s genuine relativism. Under Hales conception of relativism, the fact that “everything is relative” is inconsistent shows that genuine epistemic relativism is false. However, Hales believes that “everything true is relatively true” is a consistent relativist thesis because it presupposes the idea of necessity. Hales conception of relativism allows for propositions about necessary facts, even though those claims are relative. Hales avoids admitting that everything is possibly true under some perspective. However, he argues that everything that is necessarily true is also possibly true under some perspective. Since possibility relies on necessary truth, some propositions cohere more to necessary facts than others. Hales relativism is not genuine epistemic relativism because his account of relativism allows for propositions to have a greater or lesser epistemic value. 
◆■P ⇒ ■P, If P is relatively absolutely true then P is absolutely true.

While this proposition is only logically valid if one accepts the controversial accessibility premise S5, it is an assumption people make when considering what could be necessarily true. Hales maintains that while “everything is relative” is inconsistent “everything true is relatively true” is not. Everything true is relatively true does not entail that there is no such thing as truth, or that all views have no epistemic value. Rather, it is just an observation that if one can confirm that a proposition is relatively true, it is likely that the proposition is true, since all the propositions that can are necessarily true are also relatively true. It’s not a perfect principle for finding truth, but if one observes that the sun moves from east to west in a relative perspective, it is likely true that the sun moves from east to west. This suggests that it’s a fact that the sun moves from east to west, at least from earth. Hales suggests that language is necessarily relative, but he shows that relative claims ultimately rely on objective facts. He writes: 
“It is no more incoherent to relativize the truth of propositions to perspectives given a perspectivist semantics than it is to relativize the truth of propositions to possible worlds given a possible worlds semantics, or to relativize truth to languages given an array of languages… Relativism can be made consistent if truth is relativized to perspectives in the same way that it is relativized to possible worlds in ordinary modal logic” (Hales, 1997, p. 39-40)
This point illustrates how relative truth and objective truth in conjunction are not incoherent. Relative truth is construed in a way that creates a relationship between facts and beliefs. If a relatively true proposition has a high epistemic value, the proposition is more likely to be based on a fact. For Hales, the extent to which a relative belief P entails that is necessary determines the epistemic value. The assumption that everything necessarily true is relatively true, (■P ⇒ ◆P) and the assumption that everything relatively necessary is necessary (◆■P ⇒ ■Φ) lead Hales to conclude that any consistent relative truth has objective epistemic value, and people can evaluate which propositions are more likely to be correct (although not perfectly). There are no necessary truths that are certainly known by everyone, but there are real facts that the idea of necessary truth is supposed to represent. Facts can only be known from a relative perspective, but that does not mean that facts are relative. When one knows a fact, they have evidence for a necessary truth, but they don’t have the means to determine what facts are certainly true irrespective of their perception. Continued in Part 2…

How do you see the role of a Business Analyst in an Agile environment?

Answer: The role of a Business Analyst in an Agile environment is to act as a bridge between business stakeholders and the development team. In Agile, the BA ensures that user stories are well-defined, prioritized, and aligned with business goals. I actively participate in sprint planning, backlog grooming, and daily standups to clarify requirements and remove roadblocks. My focus is on delivering incremental value by working closely with stakeholders and ensuring the development team clearly understands the business needs.

Can you describe your experience working on projects at different stages of the SDLC?

Answer: “I’ve worked across all stages of the SDLC, from requirements gathering during the analysis phase to supporting User Acceptance Testing (UAT) and post-implementation reviews. For example, during a recent project, I gathered requirements, created functional specifications, and worked with developers during the design and development phases. I also coordinated UAT, ensuring that test cases aligned with business requirements. Post-launch, I monitored performance and gathered feedback for future iterations.”

Walk us through how you would conduct a business process assessment.

Answer: “To conduct a business process assessment, I start by defining the scope and objectives with stakeholders. Then, I gather information about the current state by interviewing key stakeholders, observing workflows, and reviewing documentation. I map out the "as-is" process using tools like BPMN. Next, I identify inefficiencies, bottlenecks, or gaps and perform a root cause analysis. Finally, I propose a "to-be" process, create a transition plan, and collaborate with stakeholders to implement the changes.”

How do you use BPMN to communicate complex processes to stakeholders?

Answer: “BPMN is a powerful tool for visualizing processes in a way that is easy to understand. I use BPMN to create diagrams that capture the flow of activities, decision points, and interactions between systems and stakeholders. For example, when working on a loan application process, I used BPMN to map out the steps from application submission to approval, highlighting areas where automation could reduce delays. This helped stakeholders visualize the process and identify areas for improvement.”

Can you explain a scenario where you used SQL to solve a business problem?

Using SQL, I wrote queries to extract data from multiple tables, joining them to create a comprehensive view of customer activity. I identified trends such as peak transaction times and high-value customers, which informed the small business’s marketing strategy. This analysis allowed the business to adapt to sales trends.”
